				<outline text="Attention mashups" created="Mon, 30 Jul 2007 18:56:35 GMT">
					<outline text="&lt;img src=&quot;http://images.scripting.com/archiveScriptingCom/2007/07/30/silo.gif&quot; width=&quot;125&quot; height=&quot;152&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;15&quot; vspace=&quot;5&quot; alt=&quot;A picture named silo.gif&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.readwriteweb.com/archives/towards_the_attention_economy_opening_silos.php&quot;&gt;ReadWriteWeb&lt;/a&gt; wonders if the &quot;attention silos&quot; will ever open up." created="Mon, 30 Jul 2007 18:56:42 GMT"/>
					<outline text="This is a long-told tale here on Scripting News. The classic &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.scripting.com/2006/09/30.html#When:10:32:44AM&quot;&gt;example&lt;/a&gt; are the movie rating data held in silos by sites like Netflix and Yahoo Movies." created="Mon, 30 Jul 2007 18:56:59 GMT"/>
					<outline text="But whose data is it?? " created="Mon, 30 Jul 2007 18:57:42 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Seems it belongs to the users and they should be able to take it where they want. Sure Yahoo is providing a recommendation engine, that's nice (and thanks), but they also get to use my data for their own purposes. Seems like a fair trade. And I'm a paying customer of Netflix. They just lowered the price but I'd much rather have gotten a dividend in the form of being able to use my own data. " created="Mon, 30 Jul 2007 19:16:17 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Think of the mashups that would be possible. " created="Mon, 30 Jul 2007 19:00:10 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Wouldn't it be &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.scripting.com/2005/05/30.html#When:6:41:31AM&quot;&gt;great&lt;/a&gt; to link up Match.com with movie ratings to find dates that like the same movies? " created="Mon, 30 Jul 2007 19:17:53 GMT"/>
					<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.hackingnetflix.com/2007/07/who-owns-your-m.html&quot;&gt;Hacking Netflix&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;Some of my Netflix Friends have rated thousands of movies, written scores of reviews, and have hundreds of movies in their queue.&quot;" created="Mon, 30 Jul 2007 23:28:20 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
