					<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.docuverse.com/blog/donpark/2007/07/05/twittergram-flash-client&quot;&gt;Don Park writes&lt;/a&gt; to say &quot;Adobe crippled audio recording in Flash so that bits from microphone are always sent directly to server-side *without* compression.&quot;" created="Thu, 05 Jul 2007 18:51:51 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="July 4" created="Wed, 04 Jul 2007 05:00:01 GMT">
				<outline text="It's the API" created="Thu, 05 Jul 2007 00:11:37 GMT">
					<outline text="Nik Cubrilovic: &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nik.com.au/archives/2007/07/03/twitter-v-pownce-its-the-api-stupid/&quot;&gt;Twitter v Pownce: It's The API, Stupid&lt;/a&gt;." created="Thu, 05 Jul 2007 00:11:41 GMT"/>
					<outline text="The API is why Twitter is a &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.scripting.com/stories/2007/04/28/twitterAsCoralReef.html&quot;&gt;coral reef&lt;/a&gt;, and Pownce is just a shipwreck." created="Thu, 05 Jul 2007 00:12:04 GMT"/>
					<outline text="&lt;img src=&quot;http://images.scripting.com/archiveScriptingCom/2007/07/04/houseOfCards.gif&quot; width=&quot;115&quot; height=&quot;112&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;15&quot; vspace=&quot;5&quot; alt=&quot;A picture named houseOfCards.gif&quot;&gt;Twitter, to me, is a very thin app, on top of a bare-bones identity system with a clean and simple API, very lightweight (and therefore not very secure, not suitable for banking applications, for example). And for not very much more complexity it's also a pub-sub system (not IM, though many people confuse it with IM). " created="Thu, 05 Jul 2007 00:17:24 GMT"/>
					<outline text="It's one of the 25 most &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.google.com/search?q=site%3Ascripting.com+twitter&quot;&gt;interesting&lt;/a&gt; pieces of software I've ever seen, not because of its technical prowess, rather because it is &lt;i&gt;not&lt;/i&gt; technically impressive. You can master it as a platform in a matter of days. With good sample code (which I didn't have) probably in hours." created="Thu, 05 Jul 2007 00:19:17 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				<outline text="Doing my part" created="Thu, 05 Jul 2007 00:39:28 GMT">
					<outline text="&lt;img src=&quot;http://images.scripting.com/archiveScriptingCom/2007/07/04/van.jpg&quot; width=&quot;131&quot; height=&quot;70&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;15&quot; vspace=&quot;5&quot; alt=&quot;A picture named van.jpg&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.docuverse.com/blog/donpark/2007/07/04/toyota-prius-and-fireworks&quot;&gt;Don Park&lt;/a&gt;, who I know to be a reasonable and fair person to do business with (I have experience), had a terrible experience with &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.toyotapaloalto.com/&quot;&gt;Magnussen's Toyota of Palo Alto&lt;/a&gt;. " created="Thu, 05 Jul 2007 00:39:31 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Part of the power of blogs is that we get to share our experiences, so we can avoid businesses that take their customers for granted. There are lots of Toyota dealers, and many of them are a pleasure to work with; again I speak from experience. " created="Thu, 05 Jul 2007 00:40:12 GMT"/>
					<outline text="I drive a Toyota myself, purchased at &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.lighthousetoyota.com/&quot;&gt;Lighthouse Toyota&lt;/a&gt; in St Augustine, FL (turn down the volume before clicking that link). I'm sure I paid more than I had to, and there were problems with the deal, but they took care of them, and in the end I felt good about the purchase. " created="Thu, 05 Jul 2007 00:45:31 GMT"/>
					<outline text="There's a big &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.toyotaofberkeley.com/&quot;&gt;Toyota dealer&lt;/a&gt; in Berkeley, I've had to bring my car in for service there, and likewise, they've done a good job, and treated me with professional care. I managed to blow out all four of my tires (they're run-flat tires, a terrible design, imho), and they replaced them at no charge. I wasn't even their customer. How about that!" created="Thu, 05 Jul 2007 00:45:39 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				<outline text="If Apple had *really* wanted to be revolutionary" created="Wed, 04 Jul 2007 22:29:39 GMT">
					<outline text="They would have made a wifi-only cell phone. " created="Wed, 04 Jul 2007 22:29:50 GMT"/>
					<outline text="I wrote about this earlier this year. As I talk with people from home on my iPhone it seems so silly. The place is saturated with wifi bandwidth, and the device uses it, for everything but telephone calls." created="Wed, 04 Jul 2007 22:29:57 GMT"/>
					<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.scripting.com/stories/2007/06/15/whyNoIphoneSdk.html#p9&quot;&gt;6/15/07&lt;/a&gt;: &quot;You gotta wonder why Apple went with such old, expensive, customer-hostile and likely obsolete technology.&quot;" created="Wed, 04 Jul 2007 22:33:01 GMT"/>
					<outline text="And then I read this &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/05/technology/circuits/05pogue.html?pagewanted=2&amp;ei=5090&amp;en=39e3cc8226651f90&amp;ex=1341288000&amp;partner=rssuserland&amp;emc=rss&quot;&gt;article&lt;/a&gt; by David Pogue in today's Times saying that T-Mobile introduced a phone last week, in the middle of all the iPhone euphoria, that routes phone calls over wifi if a signal is present." created="Wed, 04 Jul 2007 22:30:45 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Seems the iPhone should be doing that. " created="Wed, 04 Jul 2007 22:31:42 GMT"/>
					</outline>
